const e="buying-a-put",t="Buying a Put (Profiting from Drops)",o="8 min",r=[{screen_type:"hook",visual:"üìâüí∞",headline:"Make money when stocks crash",text:"October 2022: Market drops 10%. Stock investors lose $10,000. Put buyers MAKE $15,000. Same market, opposite position. This is how you profit from fear."},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"What is 'Buying a Put'?",text:"Buying a put = paying a premium for the RIGHT to sell 100 shares at your strike price by expiration. You profit when stock goes DOWN below your breakeven. Max loss = premium paid. Max profit = stock going to $0 (strike price √ó 100).",visual:"üîΩüìâ",highlight_words:["RIGHT to sell","stock goes DOWN","Max loss = premium","profit capped at $0"]},{screen_type:"key_terms",headline:"Put Buying Strategy Terms",cards:[{term:"Long Put",definition:"When you BUY a put (you're 'long')",example:"Buy to open 1 TSLA $250 put for $8.00 = you're long 1 put. You want stock to DROP."},{term:"Protective Put",definition:"Buying a put to protect stock you own",example:"Own 100 shares of AAPL at $180. Buy $170 put = insurance. If AAPL crashes to $150, your put limits loss to $10/share."},{term:"Out-of-The-Money Put (OTM)",definition:"Strike price BELOW current stock price",example:"Stock at $100, buying $90 put = OTM. Cheaper, but needs stock to fall below $90. Bearish speculation."}]},{screen_type:"analogy",headline:"Think of it like home insurance",text:"Your house is worth $500,000. You're worried about a market crash. You pay $5,000/year for insurance that guarantees you can sell it for $450,000 anytime this year...",interactive:"tap_to_reveal",reveal_sections:[{label:"Market crashes, houses now $350,000",content:"Your insurance pays! You can 'put' (sell) at $450,000 even though market is $350,000. You save $100,000 (minus $5k premium). Your neighbors lost everything."},{label:"Market stays strong at $500,000",content:"Insurance expires unused. You're out $5,000, but your house value is fine. That's the cost of protection/peace of mind."},{label:"Market skyrockets to $600,000",content:"Your house gained $100,000. You're out the $5k insurance cost, but you're still way ahead. Insurance was unnecessary but not catastrophic."},{label:"This is a protective put",content:"Premium = insurance cost. Strike = guaranteed sell price. If stock crashes, put saves you. If stock rises, you're only out the premium."}]},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"When should you buy a put option?",options:["When you think stock will go up","When you're bearish or want protection","When stock isn't moving","Never - puts are too risky"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Perfect! Buy puts when: 1) BEARISH (think stock drops), 2) HEDGING (own stock, want protection), or 3) VOLATILITY (expecting big move down). Puts are insurance OR speculation on declines.",explanation_wrong:"Remember: PUTS profit when stock goes DOWN. Buy puts when you're bearish (think price drops), or as insurance if you own the stock. Think: recession fears, earnings miss, sector rotation OUT of your stock."},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You own 100 shares of NVDA at $500. You're worried about a tech selloff. Best protective strategy?",options:["Buy a $550 put (above your cost)","Buy a $480 put (slightly below your cost)","Buy a $400 put (far below your cost)","Don't use options - just hope"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Smart hedging! The $480 put costs moderate premium and protects most of your value. If NVDA crashes to $300, you can still sell at $480. You risk $20/share ($2k) but protect against unlimited downside. Insurance that makes sense.",explanation_wrong:"Hedging 101: Choose a strike close to your cost basis. $550 = too expensive (above stock price). $400 = too cheap but you'd lose $100/share before protection kicks in. $480 = sweet spot for affordable protection."},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"Market sentiment is terrible. You don't own SPY but want to profit from a crash. What do you do?",options:["Buy a protective put (but you don't own stock)","Buy a speculative put - betting on the drop","Buy a call - stocks only go up","Puts don't work for speculation"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Exactly! This is a SPECULATIVE put (not protective). You're betting on a market drop. Buy puts on SPY, QQQ, or weak stocks. If market crashes 10%, your puts could return 200-500%. This is how traders profit from fear.",explanation_wrong:"If you don't own the stock, buying puts is SPECULATION (not hedging). You're betting on price drops. Example: Buy SPY $440 put when SPY is $450. If market crashes to $400, your put makes huge returns. Legal way to profit from crashes."},{screen_type:"calculation",question:"AAPL at $180. You buy 1 put with $170 strike for $4. AAPL crashes to $150. What's your profit in dollars? (No $ or commas)",input_type:"number",correct_answer:1600,tolerance:0,xp_reward:15,hint:"Profit = (Strike - Stock - Premium) √ó 100",explanation:"Strike $170, stock at $150 = $20 intrinsic. Minus $4 premium = $16 profit per share √ó 100 = $1,600 profit. Your put gives you the right to SELL at $170 when market is $150. That's powerful!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You bought a put for $600 as protection. Stock went UP 15%. Your put is worthless. How do you feel?",options:["Angry - you wasted $600","Happy - your stock gained more than the put cost","Neutral - it's a wash","Confused - puts should always make money"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Perfect mindset! Insurance that doesn't pay out = good thing. Your stock gained 15% (way more than $600). The put 'cost' is like car insurance you didn't use. You're protected AND profitable. That's the goal!",explanation_wrong:"Think like an insurance buyer: If your house doesn't burn down, are you mad about homeowners insurance? No! Same with protective puts. Stock went UP = great. Put expired = fine. You paid for peace of mind during uncertainty."},{screen_type:"summary_cards",headline:"Put Buying Mastery",cards:[{front:"Two reasons to buy puts?",back:"PROTECTION: Hedge stocks you own (protective put). SPECULATION: Bet on price drops (naked put). Both are valid - just different goals and risk profiles."},{front:"Max profit on a put?",back:"Limited to strike price (stock can only go to $0). Example: $100 put, stock goes to $0 = $100/share √ó 100 = $10,000 max profit. Unlike calls (unlimited), puts have a ceiling."},{front:"Put vs short selling stock?",back:"Put: Max loss = premium. Defined risk. Short stock: UNLIMITED loss potential if stock rises. Puts are safer for bearish bets - you can't lose more than you paid."}]},{screen_type:"celebration",xp_earned:80,total_xp:520,badge:"üêª Bear Trader",badge_description:"You can profit from market drops!",celebration_message:"Excellent! You now know both sides - calls AND puts. Next: understanding which options are 'in the money' and why it matters.",streak_bonus:!1,next_lesson_preview:{title:"In the Money vs Out of the Money",description:"Learn which options are profitable right now and which need movement",unlock_status:"unlocked"}}],s={lesson_id:e,title:t,estimated_time:o,screens:r};export{s as default,o as estimated_time,e as lesson_id,r as screens,t as title};
